column168: XPO Logistics terminal NML experienced a UN3109 TBHP-70-AQ release from a 5-gallon jerrican due to improper loading. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct containment and cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and advised terminal personnel had already conducted cleanup and placed the damaged jug and impacted absorbents into a closed top poly drum. The crew removed the damaged jug from the drum and placed it into a 55-gallon vented poly drum, confirming 1-gallon released. The impacted drum was then cut up and containerized along with the impacted absorbents into a separate 55-gallon vented poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal UBY experienced a UN2810 Allyl Hexanoate release from a 30-gallon metal drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct containment and cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 5-gallons of product released to a 5’ x 2’ area of the dock floor due to a forklift puncture. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted area. The damaged drum, impacted absorbents, and PPE were then collected and containerized into a 55-gallon metal drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal XWK experienced a UN3266 Flash Clene 1414 release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct containment and cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 0.55-gallons of product released to the tote body only due to a puncture. The tote was transferred from the damaged container into a new one. The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: XPO Logistics terminal XTM experienced an over the road release of UN1760 Biocide 4 from a 55-gallon poly drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct containment and cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 20-gallons of product released to a 23' x 5' area of the trailer floor and a 50’ x 2’ area of the gravel lot below due to a puncture caused by a broken pallet. The damaged drum was placed into an 85-gallon poly overpack. Floor dry and a citric acid solution were then deployed and utilized to clean the impacted areas. The impacted gravel was shoveled up and the area pH came back at a 7 once all contaminants were removed. All impacted gravel and absorbents were containerized into (3) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was transported to the XPO terminal located in Tomah, WI and staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

XPO Logistics terminal XSG experienced a UN3103 TBPB release from a box containing (4) 1-gallon poly jugs. ERTS dispatched contractors for containment and cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-cup of product released to the box only due to the vented cap releasing as a result of load shift. The jugs were removed from the impacted box and wiped down for shipment on. The impacted cardboard was neutralized with water and containerized along with the impacted rags and PPE into a vented 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: XPO Logistics terminal XCH experienced an over the road release of UN3265 DC14 from a 55-gallon poly drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct containment and cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 10-gallons of product released to a 15' x 8' area of the trailer floor and a 10' x 5' area on the concrete roadway due to a drum being tipped over in transit, causing a release from the loose bung cap. Three drums were up righted, wiped down, and secured for shipment on. Lime and absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted areas to neutralize and clean the release. All impacted absorbents were then collected into (2) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was transported to the XPO terminal located in Chicago Heights, IL and staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

On October 03, 2023, at 1049 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in Carnesville, Georgia regarding the release of approximately 2 gallons of ZAC (Corrosive liquid, n.o.s UN 1760, 8, III) from (1) 55-gallon DF. Contractors were dispatched to clean up the release with absorbents and the proper PPE.  Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release was caused by a loose bung cap and contained to the trailer floor and a small area of asphalt below the trailer. Contractors were able to clean the release and all waste generated from addressing this release was containerized in (1) 55-gallon DF and taken offsite by the contractor for proper disposal.

Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted area. The damaged jug and all cleanup debris was then collected into a 15-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.
